# Introduction {#introduction}

IDEMS has developed a bespoke RapidPro authoring system which enables partners to support chatbot development by working with content in google sheets and google docs. This system has been used to deploy several RapidPro chatbots over the past 2 years. 

In collaboration with PLH, IDEMS has built a chatbot called ParentText Crisis, which is intended to be used as a starter kit that partners can fork (duplicate) and adapt to their own purposes. IDEMS has recently worked to improve and automate some of the chatbot deployment steps, to the point where third parties can own a significant part of the chatbot authoring process.

This document outlines the steps required for a partner to deploy their own version of ParentText Crisis. While this guidance aims to be as clear as possible, it does contain technical content and language around a range of topics. It is therefore best suited to technical partners who already have some familiarity with RapidPro, GitHub and some general experience in software development.  

## **ParentText Crisis Overview** {#parenttext-crisis-overview}

ParentText Crisis has been designed such that it can be used as a starter kit for others to develop their own chatbot. There are a series of spreadsheets that are used in the production of a chatbot, detailed explanation can be found in the [Spreadsheeting System](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1UmSWSdNgfuRZe1WyNBEItGpWnUNd5D49wHkCUAZ3Pzg/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.ljqkir8qi5x4) section of the [IDEMS RapidPro Authoring Process](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1UmSWSdNgfuRZe1WyNBEItGpWnUNd5D49wHkCUAZ3Pzg/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.xpkt1jgb8s2o). In the case of ParentText Crisis, the spreadsheets have been organised across different repositories as illustrated in the diagram below.

The templates and content that is consistent across all ParentText crisis deployments is stored in the [template repo](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-templates) and the [crisis base](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-crisis-base) repo. In these repositories, the google sheets used in the chatbot have been downloaded and all stored as plain JSON files. This offers a stable versioning system to ensure that a deployment always refers to the same core content/ templates. To create an actual deployment you need a deployment specific repository, an example of such a repository can be found [here](https://github.com/ParentingForLifelongHealth/parenttext-crisis). This repository contains references to the deployment specific google sheets, as well as a reference to the other parent repos. The reference to other repos follows a hierarchy, so from the deployment repo we refer to the parent that is the crisis base repo.

![][image1]

And then from the crisis base repo we refer to the template repo. 

![][image2]

This means that when we produce a deployment from the deployment repo, all of the necessary content is fetched from the parent, and the templates are fetched from the grandparent.

For someone who is looking to produce a new ParentText deployment, it should not be necessary to modify the template repo or the content base repo, however it is important to understand the overall structure that is used to produce the chatbot. If a crisis deployment deviates significantly from the original version, then it may be necessary to make changes to the referenced repositories, but if required this should be done in collaboration with the IDEMS team.

# Creating a New Deployment  {#creating-a-new-deployment}

## **Technical Setup** {#technical-setup}

### **Copying Github Repo**

As discussed in the previous section, for each new deployment of ParentText crisis we need a deployment repo. This should be setup by first forking the [example deployment repository](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-crisis). This repository should be owned by those in charge of the content development for this particular deployment. To fork the example repository follow the [guidance here](https://docs.github.com/en/pull-requests/collaborating-with-pull-requests/working-with-forks/fork-a-repo). If necessary, the IDEMS team can support in this initial setup stage.

From reviewing this repository, you will find a readme on how to run the **pipeline**. The term **pipeline** refers to the process whereby the content from the google sheets and parent repos is processed into RapidPro flows ready to upload to a RapidPro workspace. 

### **Configuration File**

The core inputs to the **pipeline** are stored in a file **config.json** file within the deployment repository. This configuration file also contains various settings which are used to define what the final chatbot looks like (these settings are discussed in more detail later in this report). Full documentation of all of the variables in the **config.json** file can be found [here](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-pipeline/blob/main/docs/configuration.md). 

Since each deployment repo starts as a copy of the [example deployment repository](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-crisis), by default the settings will be the same as that example deployment. However, the configuration file can be modified to suit each particular deployment. If the documentation is not clear, the IDEMS team can support this config file setup process. There is one step which is essential in setting up the new configuration file, and that is to point the configuration file to the deployment specific google sheets, discussed in the subsequent section. 

## **Data List Setup** {#data-list-setup}

As discussed in the [ParentText Crisis Overview](#parenttext-crisis-overview), the spreadsheet content required to build the chatbot is organised between three repositories:

* Template Repo  
* Crisis Base Repo  
* Deployment Repo

When setting up a new deployment we should not need to edit the Template Repo or the Crisis Base Repo. In the deployment repo (which we have copied from the [example deployment repository](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-crisis)) we need to update the spreadsheets that are being referenced.

In the **config.json** file there is a list called ‘sheet names’. These sheet names are all the ids for google sheets that are specific to this deployment. The existing list of sheets are those used in the example deployment. Since we are now starting a new deployment we need to create new google sheets and update the references.

### **Copy Example Data Lists**

While it may be difficult to initially understand what each of these sheets is used for, it is important that we set up a complete set of sheets for this new deployment. Open each file in turn and select ‘save a copy’, the files should be saved in a location where all collaborations for the deployment can access. When copying the files, replace with the CT\_2.0 prefix for something that is appropriate for the deployment country, such that the new files can be easily identified. Once you have created a copy of all of the files, you then need to update the google sheet ids in the **config.json.** This is a simple process, the sheet ID of a google can be found in its URL.

![][image4]

Once these sheets have been set up and the config file updated, we now have a new deployment that is ready to be worked on. The content of the chatbot can be created by editing the google sheets, new users can review the sheets linked above to understand the content structure. The IDEMS team can support at this stage to show how and where content can be added. 

### **Language Setup in Google Sheets**

The majority of translation of the content is handled within Crowdin as explained in the section [Translations with Crowdin](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lfvKeBdTuZghuyuMDlCDvn6mSF3gBOY5RcF5zg7rlEM/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.s1uj0bk5to7) in the [IDEMS RapidPro Authoring Process](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lfvKeBdTuZghuyuMDlCDvn6mSF3gBOY5RcF5zg7rlEM/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.s1uj0bk5to7). However, there are some areas where translated content needs to be entered directly into the spreadsheets. There is also a language code that needs to be updated in some column headers. In the sample spreadsheets a placeholder of ‘lan’ has been used to indicate where the language code should be inserted. This needs to be replaced with the appropriate 3 letter language code from [ISO 639-3](https://iso639-3.sil.org/code_tables/639/data), you should also confirm that this is a valid language within RapidPro.

The sheets where translated text needs to be entered directly, or where the language code needs to be updated are explained below. All cells to be updated are highlighted in blue.

# Chatbot Development Checklist

Detailed information on Chatbot Development can be found in [\[dev\] IDEMS RapidPro Authoring Process](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1lfvKeBdTuZghuyuMDlCDvn6mSF3gBOY5RcF5zg7rlEM/edit?tab=t.0#heading=h.s1uj0bk5to7), the key steps detailed in that document that most deployers will need to address are:

- [ ] Content Authoring: Localize content using Google Sheets and/or the Google Docs Sidekick  
- [ ] Translations: The RapidPro JSON files generated from the Google Sheets need to be translated with translation consultants via Crowdin  
- [ ] Localize the Safeguarding File: Localize the file which detects predefined high-risk keywords such as 'depression,' 'anxiety,' 'danger,’ etc. and refers them to in-person support, then convert into json  
- [ ] Run GitHub Actions Pipeline: Runs several scripts, including quality assurance, …

# Ancillary Components {#ancillary-components}

## **Media Server** {#media-server}

Attachments utilised within the chatbot are stored on a dedicated server managed by IDEMS. These attachments are systematically organised into folders based on their respective types, such as voiceover (audios, videos), and images:

![][image5]

Flows executed in Rapidpro access these attachments from the server through unique URLs. Defined paths can be set up within the google sheets, these paths can be dynamically defined using RapidPro variables, as illustrated:

![][image6]

When sending an attachment through a flow, the file name is specified within the spreadsheets and then concatenated with the designated paths to enable access to the respective file.

The server housing these attachments is managed by IDEMS and caters to multiple projects, thereby precluding direct access for external parties. For any attachment-related alterations or needs, it's necessary to reach out to IDEMS. IDEMS will ensure that the files are correctly uploaded to the designated location, guaranteeing smooth functionality and conducting quality control measures. 

## **Setup of ParentText API** {#setup-of-parenttext-api}

Part of the crisis chatbot relies on webhooks used within RapidPro. The use of webhooks enables more advanced functionality and an example is explained [here](https://rapidpro.github.io/flows/examples/webhook/). In the crisis chatbot we use a webhook to specify the list of goals and modules that the user will be shown. The webhook connects to a ParentText API that has been developed by the IDEMS team, each deployment requires an associated API to be set up, this should be done in collaboration with the IDEMS team.

The details of the API can found [here](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-goals-webhooks), this can be hosted by IDEMS or by someone else if they wish. Within the API repository there is also [documentation](https://github.com/IDEMSInternational/parenttext-goals-webhooks/blob/master/docs/deploy-cloud-run.md) showing how to deploy the API through a github action. This can be setup in the deployment repository such that the API can be easily updated if there are changes.
